      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": ""
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "Schools adapt in a shrinking Los Angeles Unified"
      },
      {
        "role": "text",
        "name": "Shrinking schools are reinventing themselves as LAUSD plans a future with dramatically fewer students."
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "KATE SEQUEIRA"
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": ""
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "In the San Joaquin Valley, rapidly growing school districts endure overcrowding"
      },
      {
        "role": "text",
        "name": "As the cost of housing in the Bay Area and coastal Southern California drives families inland in search of relief, some school districts in the vast San Joaquin Valley contend with rapid enrollment growth."
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "EMMA GALLEGOS"
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "Read more"
      },
      {
        "role": "text",
        "name": "FEATURED SECTION"
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "English Learners"
      },
      {
        "role": "text",
        "name": "Almost half of California's public school students speak a language other than English in their homes. Many of those students began kindergarten still learning English. After years of English-only policies, California passed a law in 2016 allowing schools to establish bilingual programs to help more students learn more than one language, or retain their home language, while learning English. Under California's funding formula, school districts receive more funding to serve children who are English learners."
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": ""
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": ""
      },
      {
        "role": "link",
        "name": "California to boost number of bilingual teachers in Asian languages"
      },
